description: From Latin enharmonicus, from Late Latin enarmonius, from Ancient Greek ἐναρμόνιος (enarmónios), from ἐν (en)+ἁρμονία (harmonía).

entries.meaning: (music) Describing two or more identical or almost identical notes that are written differently when in different keys. (Whether they are identical depends on the tuning method used.)
examples: C sharp is enharmonic to D flat.

entries.meaning: (music) Of or pertaining to a tetrachord.
